#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""yt-show: turn a YouTube playlist into a Drivecast TV show.

Sibling CLI to stream-dl/todrive: downloads each new playlist video (via
yt-dlp) and uploads it as `<Show> SxxEyy - <Title>.ext` under
`<Show> Season N/` on a named Shared Drive, reusing renamer.py's canonical
naming and todrive's connection-string upload leg rather than duplicating
either.

Pipelined: while video N+1 downloads, video N uploads. A gap semaphore gives
backpressure so at most --max-gap (default 3) episodes are downloaded-but-not-
yet-uploaded at once — downloads pause when uploads fall behind. Per-show
incremental state (what's already uploaded, season/episode cursor) lives in
yt_shows.json next to rename_cache.json; episode numbering is per-video-id
and append-only.

Stdlib only at import time; yt_dlp is imported lazily inside probe_playlist/
download_one so `yt-show --help` and the unit tests work without it installed.

NOTE: this bypasses todrive's 100 GB overflow routing (we rclone moveto each
finished file straight into its season folder, since a lone file uploaded via
`todrive up` would land at the drive ROOT, not inside `<Show> Season N/`). A
single very large show could exceed one Shared Drive's cap -- an accepted
limitation of this pipelined path; pick another (or a fresh) drive if needed.

Crash/interruption recovery relies on two invariants the rest of the module
already has: (1) a committed episode's canonical stem is deterministic from
its stored season/episode/title, so "what's on disk" can always be compared
against "what's committed"; (2) yt-dlp only ever produces a final-shaped
filename on completion (partial writes stay under `.part`/`.ytdl`/`.aria2`,
merges land via `<stem>.temp.mp4` + `os.rename`), so a surviving final-shaped
file IS a trustworthy completion marker -- never sized, always name-shape.
Re-uploading to the same canonical dest is idempotent (`rclone moveto`
overwrites an existing dest file), so the one crash window we accept --
rc==0 on upload but killed before `save_state` commits it -- costs one
redundant re-upload on the next run, never a duplicate on the drive.

Invariant (1) has a hole staged-file reuse must guard against separately:
the canonical stem is deterministic from season/episode/title, but is NOT
guaranteed unique to one video id across runs -- clean_source_title collapses
title-less sources (e.g. plain "Episode N") to no title at all, and an
interrupted run followed by a resume where the gap gets reassigned (a video
went private, a playlist reordered) can hand that SAME bare stem to a
DIFFERENT video than the one whose staged file is sitting there. Matching by
stem alone would silently reuse the wrong video's bytes under the new one's
name. So every on-disk staged artifact carries its video id in the leaf
(`staged_download_stem`) and reuse only ever matches stem+id together; the
id is stripped back off for the actual drive destination, which stays the
plain canonical name.
"""
